{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"138f204a-fc19-4ead-8281-d813af675f37","content":"In .NET MAUI, use the **lifecycle events** API in your `MauiProgram.cs` (or app startup) via `ConfigureLifecycleEvents`:\n\n```csharp\nusing Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;\n\nbuilder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>\n{\n#if ANDROID\n    events.AddAndroid(android => android\n        .OnPause(activity =>\n        {\n            // Runs when the Android activity is paused\n        })\n        .OnStop(activity =>\n        {\n            // Runs when the Android activity is stopped\n        }));\n#elif IOS\n    events.AddiOS(ios => ios\n        .DidEnterBackground(app =>\n        {\n            // Runs when the iOS app enters background\n        }));\n#endif\n});\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- Call `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` on the `MauiAppBuilder` in `CreateMauiApp()`.\n- Use `#if ANDROID` / `#elif IOS` preprocessor directives to keep platform code separated.\n- Android exposes `OnPause`, `OnStop`, `OnResume`, `OnDestroy`, etc.\n- iOS exposes `DidEnterBackground`, `WillEnterForeground`, `WillTerminate`, etc.\n- Add `using Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;` for the extension methods.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"0ecbebe0-f92b-4dad-8065-02aee685f01b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to hook into platform-specific lifecycle events in .NET MAUI — specifically Android's `OnPause`/`OnStop` and iOS's `DidEnterBackground`. This is a general knowledge question, not a code task.","outputTokens":408},"id":"39650855-d0f7-4937-941f-f533219428d2","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:44:47.379Z","parentId":"79967ad0-1316-4759-8abd-709d21577938"}
